{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564188"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:10:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:10:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16946"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16946"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.65,0.02,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67877"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9636"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53342"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1637"},{"type":"tags","id":"4546"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"10948"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43672"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67877"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with her partner with a three-year history of primary infertility. She reports regular menstrual cycles with severe dysmenorrhoea. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her partner\u0027s semen analysis is normal. Her anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone level is 25 pmol/L (14-30), and hysterosalpingogram shows patent fallopian tubes. Diagnostic laparoscopy reveals stage II endometriosis with endometriotic deposits on the uterosacral ligaments and ovarian surfaces.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["In vitro fertilisation","Laparoscopic excision of endometriosis","Expectant management","Combined oral contraceptive pill","Gonadotropin-releasing hormone analogue therapy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with primary infertility and is found to have stage II endometriosis on diagnostic laparoscopy. All other fertility investigations are normal. The presence of endometriosis can affect fertility through various mechanisms including altered peritoneal environment, impaired implantation, and distorted pelvic anatomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic excision\u003C/strong\u003E of endometriosis is the most appropriate management in this case. Multiple studies have shown that surgical treatment of minimal to mild endometriosis (stage I/II) improves fertility outcomes. The procedure allows for both diagnosis and treatment in the same setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate given the confirmed presence of endometriosis and the long duration of infertility. Without intervention, the endometriosis is likely to progress and further impact fertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadotropin-releasing hormone analogue\u003C/strong\u003E therapy suppresses ovulation and is therefore counterproductive in a woman actively trying to conceive. While it may improve endometriosis symptoms, it does not enhance fertility outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIn vitro fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered if surgical treatment fails or if there are other fertility factors present. It is generally not first-line treatment for stage II endometriosis with otherwise normal fertility investigations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E therapy may help with symptom control but is contraindicated in someone trying to conceive as it prevents ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Laparoscopic excision of endometriosis improves fertility outcomes in women with stage I/II endometriosis.","A diagnostic laparoscopy should be considered in cases of unexplained infertility.","Endometriosis staging correlates poorly with fertility outcomes but guides management decisions."],"references":["Hamilton KM, VanHise K, Truong MD, Wright KN, Siedhoff MT. Surgical management of endometriosis to optimize fertility. Curr Opin Obstet Gynecol. 2023 Aug 1;35(4):389-394. doi: 10.1097/GCO.0000000000000876. Epub 2023 Apr 25. PMID: 37144586.","Practice Committee of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine. Endometriosis and infertility. Fertil Steril. 2006 Nov;86(5 Suppl 1):S156-60. doi: 10.1016/j.fertnstert.2006.08.014. PMID: 17055813."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53342"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16946"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53342"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T16:53:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T16:54:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9636"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67877"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null